values:
I feel like something has happened nearly every damn day of the last months when I've blocked off time to go running.&nbsp; 

1/3 of the time it's work stuff, and you better believe I'm going to drop everything and run like hell for that fire drill (um, hello, I want a job in 2010).&nbsp; 

but now another 1/3 of the time it's been baby stuff -- our poor kid has been home sick with a fever for what feels like 50% of the last month -- all of which culminated in a trip to the murray hill doctor's office today.&nbsp; (&quot;yup, he's got roseola.&nbsp; no, he won't feel or look or act sick at all.&nbsp; but he'll still be running a fever, which according to new york state law means that you can't send him to daycare.&nbsp; why mrs. o'keefe, why are you grimacing?&quot;).&nbsp; 

and the remaining 1/3 gets neatly divided between doing my regular work (which takes longer than I thought it would) and, well, obssessively haunting the pantry and water cooler and starbucks and pret for fellow helth-wyzer folk news of the next reorg, and gossip on its possible implications.&nbsp; life has been like this for the past four and a half years so I don't know why I care anymore, but when you're working at the largest pharmaceutical company in the world and people actually care how you structure your business, it makes even tech geeks like me perk up and take notice.&nbsp; that, and little old MBA&nbsp;me has dreams of writing all this shit up in an HBR&nbsp;case someday.

anyway!&nbsp; back to bitching about not running.&nbsp; so for the most part I'm thrilled that james decided to wean himself.&nbsp; (mostly.)&nbsp; I certainly don't miss lugging a big-ass breast pump around with me as if I were just waiting for the opportunity to whip open my shirt and feed starving orphans in africa.&nbsp; &quot;open wide, kids!&quot;&nbsp; but, that was also 500 calories a day or so that I am no longer burning.&nbsp; in the first month alone post-wean I've put on four pounds.&nbsp; you couple that with a really, really shitty running schedule and I am NOT&nbsp;a happy camper.&nbsp; 

thank god all my clothes still fit.&nbsp; it's winter wardrobe season now and I haven't worn most of this stuff since 2006.&nbsp; party on wayne!
